            <creation>This story, with the short title "Icon Next to a Couple's Bed," is recent: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1850</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>A man named Walda Iyasus describes how a certain icon of Mary passed into the hands of a man named Aleqa Tessema, who was the head scribe for the king of Gojjam. Aleqa Tessema purchased the icon from some pilgrims and brought it to Jerusalem. Although he devoted himself to this icon, he installed it in an impure place—that is, on a pedestal near the bed where he slept with his wife. Walda Iyasus tells how this icon appeared to him in a dream. The icon called out to him and told him about how Aleqa Tessema had put her in an unseemly place. She then instructed him to go visit Aleqa Tessema and convince him to place her in the church of St. George in the town of Od Teklay. Walda Iyasus did as Mary instructed, and when he told Aleqa Tessema of his vision, the scribe acted immediately. He gave this icon, as well as a second icon he’d purchased in Hamasen, to his servant, who then delivered them to churches in the Gojjam region. The first icon went to the monastery of Martula Maryam, and the other went to Dabbo. Walda Iyasus concludes by describing how the icon appeared to him again, asking him to record this miracle story.</p>
